cout << 1 + ( rand() {0} 9 ) << endl;

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Random Numbers[/h1]

Use the [b]modulo [/b](%) operator to generate random numbers within a specific range.
The example below generates whole numbers within a range of 1 to 6. [code format="cpp" codeId="241"]int main () {
  for (int x = 1; x <= 10; x++) {
  cout << [b]1 + (rand() % 6) [/b]<< endl;
  }
}

/* Output: 
6
6
5
5
6
5
1
1
5
3
*/[/code]
[note]However, the [b]rand()[/b] function will only return a pseudo random number. This means that each time the code is run, it generates the same numbers.[/note]

[h1]The srand() Function[/h1]

The [b]srand()[/b] function is used to generate truly random numbers.
This function allows to specify a [b]seed[/b] value as its parameter, which is used for the [b]rand()[/b] function's algorithm. [code format="cpp" codeId="242"]int main () {
  [b]srand(98);
[/b]
  for (int x = 1; x <= 10; x++) {
    cout << 1 + (rand() % 6) << endl;
  }
}[/code]
[note]Changing the seed value changes the return of rand(). However, the same argument will result in the same output.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print to the screen a truly random number from 1 through 15, generated by the rand() function.
[!raw!]
{0}( time(0) );
cout << 1 + (rand() % {1}) << endl;

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Truly Random Numbers[/h1]

A solution to generate truly random numbers, is to use the current time as a seed value for the srand() function.
This example makes use of the [b]time()[/b] function to get the number of seconds on your system time, and randomly seed the rand() function (we need to include the [b]<ctime>[/b] header for it): [code format="cpp" codeId="243"]#include <iostream>
#include <cstdlib>
[b]#include <ctime>[/b]
using namespace std;

int main () {
[b]  srand(time(0));
[/b]
  for (int x = 1; x <= 10; x++) {
    cout << 1 + (rand() % 6) << endl;
  }
}[/code]
[b]time(0)[/b] will return the current second count, prompting the [b]srand()[/b] function to set a different seed for the [b]rand()[/b] function each time the program runs.
[note]Using this seed value will create a different output each time we run the program.[/note]
